Assumtion 2: Model Errors are centered at 0

The quick and dirty way would be to look at the center of the histogram. We can also perform a statistical test:

t.test(chol_mod$residuals, alternative = "two.sided", mu = 0)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  chol_mod$residuals
## t = 4.219e-15, df = 3141, p-value = 1
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1.50336  1.50336
## sample estimates:
##    mean of x 
## 3.234905e-15

0 is dead-set in the middle of the confidence interval. We’re rather confident that the mean of the residuals is close enough to 0. In hypotheses test, you can say something is wrong, but you can’t say something is true.(Maybe this is why we can just say “fail to reject h0”" but not “accept h0”)

Assumption 3: Model Errors are Homoskedastic

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(chol_mod)

# We can see from the first plot (residuals vs fitted) that there are amoset
# completely random and equal distribution of points throughout the range of x
# axis and a flat red line. So we can say that the model errors are homoskedastic.
